    "pathophysiology": "A small gallstone passes from the gallbladder through the cystic duct into the common bile duct. It transiently or persistently occludes the pancreatic duct at the ampulla of Vater. This obstructs pancreatic exocrine secretion, leading to activation of trypsinogen within the pancreas (premature activation). The activated trypsin triggers autodigestion of pancreatic tissue, causing inflammation, edema, and potentially necrosis. The CBD may remain obstructed by the impacted stone or by edema from the inflamed pancreatic head, producing jaundice. Passage of the stone can cause jaundice to fluctuate.",
